#The exercise solution appears broken, so mine took a totally different path.
figure, axis = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(8, 7))
for n, species in enumerate(iris['Species'].unique()):
    df = iris[iris['Species'] == species]
    axis[n].boxplot([df[col] for col in iris.columns[:-1]])
    axis[n].set_title(species, loc='left')
    axis[n].set_xlim(0.5, len(iris.columns[:-1]) + 0.5)
    axis[n].set_ylim(0.0, iris[iris.columns[:-1]].max().max() * 1.05)
    axis[n].set_xticklabels([col[:-2] for col in iris.columns[:-1]],rotation=45, fontsize=10)
figure.suptitle("General Statistics for Iris Dataset = Boxplots")
figure.supylabel("Size in centimeters (cm)")
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.89, wspace=0.3, left=0.08)
plt.show()

fig = iris[iris.Species=='Iris-setosa'].plot(kind='scatter',x='SepalLengthCm',y='SepalWidthCm',color='orange', label='Setosa')
iris[iris.Species=='Iris-versicolor'].plot(kind='scatter',x='SepalLengthCm',y='SepalWidthCm',color='blue', label='versicolor',ax=fig)
iris[iris.Species=='Iris-virginica'].plot(kind='scatter',x='SepalLengthCm',y='SepalWidthCm',color='green', label='virginica', ax=fig)
fig.set_xlabel("Sepal Length")
fig.set_ylabel("Sepal Width")
fig.set_title("Sepal Length VS Width")
fig=plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(12,8)
plt.show()

  1. Write a Python program to create a joinplot using "hexbin" to describe individual distributions on the same plot between Sepal length and Sepal width.

Note: The bivariate analogue of a histogram is known as a "hexbin" plot, because it shows the counts of observations that fall within hexagonal bins. This plot works best with relatively large datasets. It's available through the matplotlib plt.hexbin function and as a style in jointplot(). It looks best with a white background.

Note: The kernel density estimation (kde) procedure visualize a bivariate distribution. In seaborn, this kind of plot is shown with a contour plot and is available as a style in jointplot().
